    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** - May 26, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🧢 Gig work becomes robot homework\n\nPhysical AI has found a new training set: people doing real chores while wearing camera hats. Elegant, if your definition of elegant includes consent screens and mop water.\n\n- **The raise:** Human Archive raised $8.2 million from Wing VC, NVP Capital, Y Combinator and angels tied to OpenAI, Nvidia, Google and Meta.\n- **The rig:** The startup says it has 1,000+ active headsets in India and 50+ devices collecting RGB-D video, wrist camera, tactile, and motion-capture data.\n- **The catch:** Customers get discounted services if they consent to recording; workers get a $1 hourly base, while Indian officials are reportedly reviewing consent practices.\n\n*The robots are learning housework. The labor model, tragically, already graduated.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/26/human-archive-taps-into-indias-services-startups-to-collect-data-for-physical-ai/)\n\n---\n\n## 🧮 ByteDance shops for its own silicon spine\n\nThe AI agent race has reached the part where chatbots need custom chips by the million, because apparently GPUs were too straightforward.\n\n- **The deal:** Bloomberg reports Qualcomm reached an agreement to supply ByteDance with millions of ASICs for AI data centers supporting Doubao, the TikTok owner's flagship chatbot.\n- **The signal:** Qualcomm shares jumped more than 5% after the report, a useful reminder that inference hardware is now an actual growth pitch.\n- **The politics:** The deal lands inside China's push to reduce dependence on Nvidia while U.S. export controls keep turning chip procurement into a diplomatic obstacle course.\n\n*Doubao gets agents; Qualcomm gets relevance; everyone else gets another spreadsheet labeled sovereignty.*\n\n**Sources:** [Bloomberg](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-05-26/qualcomm-strikes-ai-chip-deal-with-tiktok-owner-bytedance) | [Techmeme](https://www.techmeme.com/river)\n\n---\n\n## 🔀 OpenRouter sells the model switchboard\n\nThe winning AI stack may be less one god model and more a router deciding which expensive brain gets this particular invoice.\n\n- **The round:** OpenRouter raised a $113 million Series B led by CapitalG; TechCrunch says the post-money valuation is about $1.3 billion.\n- **The load:** The company says it now processes 100 trillion tokens per month, or 25 trillion per week, up 5x from six months ago.\n- **The catalog:** Its gateway gives access to 400+ models from providers including Anthropic, Google, OpenAI, xAI and DeepSeek, with more than 8 million users.\n\n*Vendor lock-in is still alive. It just learned to wear a routing table.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/26/openrouter-more-than-doubles-valuation-to-1-3b-in-a-year/) | [Business Wire](https://www.afp.com/en/infos/openrouter-raises-113-million-capitalg-led-series-b-weekly-volume-explodes-25t-tokens)\n\n---\n\n## 🚕 Pony.ai trots past the pilot phase\n\nRobotaxis remain a beautiful business where the car drives itself and the spreadsheet still needs adult supervision.\n\n- **The quarter:** Pony AI reported Q1 revenue of $34.3 million, up 145% year over year, while robotaxi revenue rose 395.4% and fare-charging revenue climbed 456.5%.\n- **The fleet:** The company says it has more than 1,700 robotaxis and raised its 2026 year-end target from 3,000 to over 3,500 vehicles.\n- **The map:** Pony expanded in Guangzhou, initiated commercial robotaxi service in Croatia, and says it is starting driverless deployments in Dubai.\n\n*Autonomy is scaling. Profitability may still request a human safety driver.*\n\n**Sources:** [Pony AI](https://ir.pony.ai/news-releases/news-release-details/pony-ai-inc-reports-first-quarter-2026-financial-results) | [The Motley Fool](https://www.fool.com/earnings/call-transcripts/2026/05/26/pony-ai-pony-q1-2026-earnings-transcript/)\n\n---\n\n## 🛂 Beijing puts AI talent on a leash\n\nChina's AI race is now so strategic that the human weights may need permission to board a plane.\n\n- **The curb:** Bloomberg reports Chinese agencies are restricting overseas travel for top AI professionals at private firms including Alibaba and DeepSeek.\n- **The test:** People are reportedly being selected by how important their work is to China's AI ambitions, not only by rank or employer.\n- **The point:** The move extends sensitive-sector controls into private AI labs as Beijing tries to prevent technology leaks while closing the gap with U.S. model and chip ecosystems.\n\n*Talent retention is easier when airport permission becomes part of the org chart.*\n\n**Sources:** [Reuters via MarketScreener](https://www.marketscreener.com/news/china-restricts-overseas-travel-for-top-ai-talent-at-alibaba-and-deepseek-bloomberg-news-reports-ce7f5adddc8ff322) | [Tom's Hardware](https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/artificial-intelligence/chinese-ai-experts-in-private-firms-now-required-to-secure-approval-before-international-travel-beijing-enforces-policy-to-secure-top-tier-talent-expands-measures-beyond-government)"
  }
]
